{{Infobox event
| image = 500mb Height Field & 2m Temperature at 0z September 6th, 2000 - Central US Heat Wave.jpg
| caption = MERRA2 data showing 2-meter temperature (in&nbsp;°C) and 500-[[millibar]] height fields at 7&nbsp;p.m.&nbsp;CDT on September 5, 2000.
| duration = July–September 2000
}}
Aided by [[drought]], a [[heat wave]] persisted in the late summer of 2000 along the [[Southern United States|southern tier]] of the [[United States]] from July to early September.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/sotc/drought/200016#Heat|title=Drought - Summer (JJA) 2000 {{!}} State of the Climate |publisher= [[National Centers for Environmental Information|NCEI]]|language=en|access-date=2017-05-04}}</ref> Near the end of the period, daily, monthly, and even all-time record high temperatures were broken, with highs commonly peaking well over 100&nbsp;°F (38&nbsp;°C). On September 4, [[Houston]] hit 109&nbsp;°F (42.8&nbsp;°C) and [[Dallas]] peaked at 111&nbsp;°F (43.9&nbsp;°C).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wunderground.com/history/airport/KDFW/2000/9/5/MonthlyHistory.html|title=Weather History for Dallas/Ft Worth, TX |website=[[Weather Underground (weather service)|Weather Underground]]|access-date=2017-05-04}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=September 2018}} On September 5, [[Corpus Christi, Texas|Corpus Christi]] peaked at 109&nbsp;°F (42.8&nbsp;°C)<ref name="NCDC2000">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/oa/climate/extremes/2000/september/septemberext2000.html#TEMPERATURE|title=September 2000 City/State Extremes|last=Ross|first=Tom|publisher=[[National Climatic Data Center|NCDC]]|access-date=2017-05-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170511172133/https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/oa/climate/extremes/2000/september/septemberext2000.html#TEMPERATURE|archive-date=2017-05-11|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> and [[San Antonio]] rose to an all-time high of 111&nbsp;°F (43.9&nbsp;°C),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wunderground.com/history/airport/KSAT/2000/9/5/MonthlyHistory.html|title=Weather History for San Antonio, TX |website= Weather Underground |access-date=2017-05-04}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=September 2018}} while [[College Station, Texas|College Station]] and [[Austin, Texas|Austin]] reached 112&nbsp;°F (44.4&nbsp;°C).<ref name="NCDC2000" /> Damage totaled $4 billion, mainly due to [[wildfire]]s and [[Harvest#Crop failure|crop losses]], and there were 140 deaths.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/monitoring-content/billions/docs/lott-and-ross-2003.pdf|title=A Climatology of 1980-2003 Extreme Weather and Climate Events|first1 = Tom |last1 = Ross| first2 = Neal |last2 = Lott|date= December 2003 |publisher= [[National Climatic Data Center|NCDC]] |language=en|access-date=2018-09-01}}</ref>

